<br>
And yet, there are many prominent conservatives who believe that drugs should be legalized, notwithstanding any of the unfortunate consequences of addiction to such drugs.  The list of conservatives is quite impressive:  Wm. F. Buckley, Milton Friedman, ex-Sec'y of State George Schulz, Rep. Dana Rohrbacher R - CA, ex-Gov. Gary Johnson.<br>
<br>
Since I believe drugs should be carefully legalized, I will make the argument for this side.  Perhaps someone would care to make the argument in favor of continuing Prohibition.  <br>
<br>
Bear in mind, I want to focus solely on <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>conservative</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> arguments.  And to eliminate the pejorative label of &quot;illegal&quot; or &quot;mind-altering&quot;, I will refer to these drugs as &quot;intoxicants&quot;.<br>
<br>
1.  <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Liberty</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->  As a general rule, here in the land of the free, people should be allowed to do anything they choose to do unless it demonstrably hurts someone else.  It is difficult to prove how moderate recreational intoxication hurts anyone other than the user, who presumably can make a decision for himself as to how he lives his life.<br>
<br>
In contrast, socialist thought asserts that the gov't knows what is best for all.  It despises individual thought and autonomy which must be suppressed for the good of the state.  What good conservative could support this?<br>
<br>
2.  <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Federalism </strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> The U.S. Consititution does not empower the Federal gov't to control the distribution of intoxicants.  Thus, according to the principle of federalism, the right to use drugs and the power to restrict those rights, belongs to the people and to the states.<br>
<br>
In contrast, socialism teaches that the central gov't is empowered to do whatever the gov't decides to do.  They can control any and every aspect of your life, for the good of the community.  What good conservative could support this?<br>
<br>
3.  <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Free markets</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->  Drug prohibition is the worst kind of manipulation of what otherwise would be a free market.  By attempting to ban distribution of certain intoxicating substances, the gov't succeeds only in creating a black market.  Prohibition laws discourage, but do not eliminate the market.  However, the end result is that supply is vastly reduced and the price is driven sky-high, according to the familiar law of supply and demand.<br>
<br>
Consumers of such intoxicants are perfectly willing to ignore the law in order to get what they want.  But since drug distributors risk going to jail, they charge a premium.  And since the price is so high, intoxicants are priced way higher than they would be in an open market.<br>
<br>
Because prices are so high, many consumers can no longer afford these intoxicants, so they steal.  Thus, it is Drug Prohibition that introduces drug violence and crime and predatory pricing into our society.  Show me one sane individual who favors continued high crime in our society.  Neither conservatives nor liberals support this.<br>
<br>
4.  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">Compassion</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Because these intoxicating substances are illegal, users who abuse them often do not seek help to overcome their problem.  Legalization would reduce the stigma associated with addiction to a level approaching the stigma of alcoholism and nicotine addiction.  One can imagine advertisements on TV for a &quot;methadone patch&quot; to help people kick opiate addiction.<br>
<br>
Why did Rush Limbaugh keep his addiction a secret?  Because it was illegal.  Had it been legal, perhaps he would have sought help sooner, perhaps before he lost his hearing.<br>
<br>
Also, the worst aspects of marijuana usage are the harmful substances the user inhales.  In a legal market, the active ingredient in pot could be packaged as a harmless inhaled mist or as nose drops.  This would greatly reduce pot-smoking and make marijuana an almost completely harmless intoxicant.<br>
<br>
Moreover, one of the worse dangers of injectible drugs (such as heroin) is the risk of AIDS and hepatitis infection via shared needles.  It is likely that this danger could be mitigated if drugs were distributed safely and legally.<br>
<br>
5.  <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Rule of Law</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->  These intoxicants are extremely popular.  They are popular despite being illegal.  They remain popular despite the approbation of society.  It is estimated that there are tens of millions of Americans who use one or more of these substances on a monthly basis.<br>
<br>
Tens of millions!  A CD that sells half a million copies is called a &quot;Gold Record&quot;; a million copies is called &quot;Platinum&quot;; they even have a name for a disc that sells 10 million -- they call it a &quot;Diamond Record&quot;.  If Marijuana were a recording artist, it would produce at least one Diamond Record every month.<br>
<br>
That's pretty popular.<br>
<br>
Whenever society tries to squelch a popular behavior, even if it is popular with only a fraction of the population, it never succeeds in eliminating the behavior.  Alcohol could not be successfully prohibited, no matter how noble that idea was.  Cigarettes cannot be prohibited.  Try as we might, we will never stop a majority of Americans from breaking the speed limit on a regular basis (think about that next time you are driving to or from work).<br>
<br>
Every time someone breaks one of these &quot;unpopular&quot; laws, he is showing a disrespect for the rule of law.  After a while, obeying the law almost seems optional, rather than compulsory.  Is this a good thing?<br>
<br>
Unlike speeding, which is a threat to public safety and must be policed no matter how unpopular speed limits are, illegal intoxicants harm only the user (except, of course, for driving while intoxicated, which is also a public safety issue).  By trying to prohibit private personal behavior (where public safety is not at risk), we are actually discouraging respect for the rule of law.  It tears at the fabric of society.<br>
<br>
Given that we know that drug prohibition will never succeed, would we not be better off concentrating our law enforcement efforts on laws that are not frequently and popularly violated, or on those which public safety dictates vigilant attention?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE HR START--><hr /><!--EZCODE HR END--><br>
<br>
In conclusion, the War on Drugs demonstrates big government at its worst and most ineffective.  It ends up harming those it purports to defend.  It creates a an artificial black market, causing harm to consumers (higher prices) and even crime and violence.<br>
<br>
It permits the central gov't to usurp powers that belong to the states and ultimately to individuals against whom the war is being waged.  And it tears at the fabric of society, weakening the bonds that tie us together as a community.<br>
<br>
And, worst of all, it is an offense to those who died to preserve our Liberty.  Men did not shed their blood and risk life and limb to make the State more powerful.  They did it so that we all could breathe free. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000028><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bfcavconservatives.showUserPublicProfile?gid=therightguyatfcav>The Right Guy at FCAV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(12/30/03 10:39 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/ffcavconservativesfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=14.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Drug legalization: a conservative position</span><hr size=1> In my opinion, legalizing drugs is NOT a Conservative position!<br>
