<br>
&gt;&gt; 1. Have you ever been around someone that is addicted to crack? <br>
<br>
Yes.  No more pitiful than an alcoholic.<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt; Do you think that legalizing it will help moderate the down time during the lows.<br>
<br>
Legalization would obviously have no effect on the bad side-effects of the drug.  Legal cigarettes do not make them any less lethal.<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt; Or should employers have a 20 minute break every hour for those that need a quick fix. <br>
<br>
As they now do for lethal cigarettes?  No, of course not.  Why would employers hire crack addicts, or tolerate them if it were affecting the job?  It would be the same if someone had an alcohol addiction.<br>
<br>
2. Have you ever been around someone that is at a party, with plenty of coke to go around, but not enough money to pick any up? <br>
<br>
Addicts are a sad lot.  But I have known far more people who have used coke for a little while and decided it wasn't worth the bother.  It is just like the legal drugs of alcohol &amp; tobacco, some people get addicted and most do not.<br>
<br>
&gt; Sexual favors are always an option, but what about moral fiber. Should we just throw that out the door? <br>
<br>
If you don't think people don't do sexual favors for alcohol, you haven't been to many bars.  &quot;Buy you a drink, sweetie?&quot;.<br>
<br>
&gt; The United States of coke heads sounds just great by me. <br>
<br>
Instead of the US of alcohol?  Does legal alcohol make us the US of alcohol?  Of course not.  We are not defined by the reprobates amongst us (and I consider drug addicts to be pitiful reprobates who are more harmed by the drug war than helped).<br>
<br>
&gt; What about the lawyer that has not had a line since yesterday morning. He has the shakes, cold sweats, feels faint. <br>
<br>
What about the surgeon who is addicted legal pain killers that he can prescribe himself?  This does not constitute an argument against using these substances within reason.  I cannot play basketball worth a damn, should we outlaw basketball because of my reaction to it?<br>
<br>
3. A truck driver barrels right into a preschool, the police report says he was using crank for 2 days, and unable to sleep. Sure you could say that one could be drunk also, but the problem there is that you can smell alcohol, you cannot smell crank. <br>
<br>
First of all, if a driver were to kill someone (whether it was in a preschool or a funeral parlor -- notice how you picked a particularly soft target, as if who died in the car accident were important), the police would do a prompt blood test and screen for any intoxicant, including &quot;crank&quot;.<br>
<br>
&gt; To me, this is not a debate on politics. This is a debate in sociology. <br>
<br>
I am not sure what that means.  Our politics shape our laws and our laws shape and are shaped by society.  But in America, we're supposed to be free to run our own laws.  My father chose to smoke cigarettes and died at age 63 from emphysema.  Perfectly legal.  Really stupid.  But even more stupid would be to make this very dangerous addictive drug illegal.<br>
<br>
&gt; I would be hard-pressed, without getting into a medical debate, arguing with you on the green thc. <br>
<br>
So, let's start by legalizing pot.  THC is not known to be harmful in any way.  Inhaling it along with poisonous smoke is probably not a good idea, but if it were legal people would find safer ways to inhale it.<br>
<br>
&gt; I have a good buddy that does it often, and he works for a bank, and goes to school full time....<br>
<br>
Like most pot smokers, he is a valuable, contributing, tax-paying member of society and probably nobody would guess he smokes.  He shows no harmful effects.  So why are we punishing all pot smokers because of coke addicts.<br>
<br>
&gt; Problem with the wacky weed is it really is a gateway drug. <br>
<br>
I really doubt there is any evidence to support this.  You can draw stronger correlations between alcohol, coffee and chocolate and future cocaine use.  There are many coke users who have never used pot or at least not used it very often.  But there are very few who have not tried coffee and chocolate -- some even use these substances every day! &lt;gasp&gt;  But saying that a coke user started out with chocolate doesn't explain why such use <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>led to</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> coke use, if it did at all.  You can look at the number of chocolate users who did not go on to become coke addicts, but then you can also look at the vast majority of pot users who do not choose to do coke.  They are very different drugs with entirely different physiological and cognitive effects.<br>
<br>
&gt; After a few years, you have to smoke so much of it to get the same results you once had, it seems easier to just step it up a notch to coke.<br>
<br>
This is utter bull poop.  There is almost no effect of THC on the brain the day after you smoke.  There is almost no effect on the body after a few days.  And it is undetectable in the body after 30 days or so.  It is not known to cause heart disease (as is tobacco &amp; alcohol), nor liver disease (as is alcohol).  It does not cause brain damage.  It is one of the most biologically inert substances one can ingest (after water and chalk, I suppose).<br>
<br>
And why is it that you think it is just a notch up to coke.  There is a far stronger correlation between alcohol and tobacco abuse and coke abuse.<br>
<br>
&gt; Seen it many times. <br>
<br>
Pardon me if I do not believe you.<br>
<br>
&gt; Also, and I am not a medical expert, but this same buddy...<br>
<br>
The problem here is that such stories are apocryphal and anecdotal.  Medical studies are all that we should really rely on and unfortunately one of the worst consequences of drug prohibition is that we don't do good studies on drug use.  If we did we'd find that it is not as bad as we think (we know this because such studies are being done elsewhere -- check out the facts at www.norml.org).<br>
<br>
&gt; Alcohol can be consumed by very many without them becoming addicted.<br>
<br>
And no one is really physically addicted to pot -- the level of addiction to alcohol is much higher, as is the threshold of use which gets people addicted (meaning that it's easier to get hooked on alcohol).<br>
<br>
&gt; Same goes with cigarettes. <br>
<br>
Nicotine is the most addictive substance known to man.  I don't know many people who find it easy to stop smoking cigarettes.  I even think that most people who smoke for even a short length of time become addicted.  So I think you've blundered on this point.<br>
<br>
&gt; You can not say that about all the other drugs. <br>
<br>
Pot is not at all addictive.  The other drugs are, but none are more addictive than tobacco, with alcohol in second place (above even heroin!).  I wish I could find the study that claimed this.  But, I will grant that one study (which I can't even cite correctly) does not prove the point.  <br>
<br>
&gt; Of course this varies by person, but I am talking in overall numbers here.<br>
<br>
One need only look at the US population to see that we have many millions more tobacco and alcohol addicts than we even have people using these other drugs that you claim are so addictive.  That would seem to argue against your point.<br>
<br>
&gt; How often have you heard of someone breaking into a house to steal goods that could then be sold that would enable him or her to buy a 40oz beer, or a pack of smokes.<br>
<br>
Make them illegal and watch out.<br>
<br>
&gt; Now you chime in, but if it where legal. Just stop right there. Even if it where legal, the addiction will still have the same affect, and unlike beer or smokes, you have to have it now, and if you cannot afford it, you will find a way. <br>
<br>
I don't think you know many drunks then.<br>
<br>
&gt; I think you need to actually be around those that are addicted to &quot;heavy drugs&quot; before you come on here and write an essay about why we as freedom loving people should allow them to be just that, free.(not in economic terms)<br>
<br>
I have been.  I feel sorry for these people.  I hope they get their lives together.  But even nice guys like Rush Limbaugh can have addiction problems.  At least we're better off with prescription drugs because we can track the distribution.  With totally illegal drugs we have no idea who's using and who isn't.<br>
<br>
But we should not make our country a worse place to live and waste $20 billion in federal money every year in a drug war that has not ever been successful (and never will succeed), just to prevent a slim minority of screwups from ruining their lives.  The trade-off is just not there.<br>
